<%= faq_schema([
  { question: "What is Docker Compose?", answer: "Docker Compose is a tool for defining and running multi-container Docker applications. You describe your services in a YAML file called docker-compose.yml, specifying images, ports, volumes, environment variables, and dependencies. A single command (docker compose up) starts all the services together, making it ideal for local development environments and simple deployments." },
  { question: "What services does this generator support?", answer: "This generator supports PostgreSQL, MySQL, Redis, MongoDB, Nginx, Node.js, Ruby on Rails, Elasticsearch, RabbitMQ, Memcached, MailHog for email testing, and MinIO for S3-compatible storage. Each service includes sensible defaults for ports, environment variables, volumes, and health checks." },
  { question: "How do volumes work in Docker Compose?", answer: "Named volumes persist data between container restarts. When a container is removed, its named volumes are preserved unless explicitly deleted. For databases like PostgreSQL and MySQL, volumes ensure your data survives container recreation. Bind mounts (starting with ./) map local directories into the container for live code reloading during development." },
  { question: "What are health checks?", answer: "Health checks verify that a service is ready to accept connections. Docker periodically runs the health check command and marks the container as healthy, unhealthy, or starting. This is especially important for databases that need time to initialize. Other services can use depends_on with condition: service_healthy to wait for dependencies to be fully ready." },
  { question: "How do I customize the generated file?", answer: "The generated file provides a solid starting point. Customize it by changing image tags to specific versions, adjusting environment variables for your project, modifying port mappings to avoid conflicts, adding networks for service isolation, and including additional volumes for configuration files. Always change default passwords before using in any shared environment." }
]) %>

